cs.CG, cs.DM, cs.GT, cs.NA, cs.SY. 

The paper deals with the problem of computing a triangulation of a geometric object, which is a fundamental problem in computational geometry. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves combinatorial arguments and graph theory, which suggests that it could also belong to cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory). The algorithmic aspect of the paper and the use of the RAM model of computation make cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) a possible sub-category as well. Finally, the paper discusses the real projective plane, which is a topic in control theory and robotics, indicating that it could also belong to cs.SY (Systems and Control).
